2,"title":"Pension contributions: tax relief","body":"\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You automatically get tax relief on contributions to your own pension.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>How you get the tax relief depends on the type of pension scheme you&rsquo;re paying into. </p>\n\n<h2>Workplace pension schemes</h2>\n\n<p>Your employer may take pension contributions from your pay before they take Income Tax away. This is called a &lsquo;net pay arrangement&rsquo;.</p>\n\n<p>So you don’t pay Income Tax on your pension contributions (but you do pay National Insurance contributions on them). </p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>Not all workplace pensions use these arrangements - ask your employer if it applies to you.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Personal pensions</h2>\n\n<p>You’ve already paid tax on the income you pay into a personal pension. </p>\n\n<p>For all personal pensions and some workplace pension schemes, your pension provider claims back Income Tax at the basic 20% rate and adds it to your pension pot. This is called a &lsquo;relief at source&rsquo; arrangement.</p>\n\n<p>This means for every £80 you pay into your pension, you end up with £100 in your pension pot. </p>\n\n<p>If you pay Income Tax at the 40% rate, you can claim back the extra 20% tax you&rsquo;ve paid on your pension contributions through your <a href=\"/self-assessment-tax-returns\" title=\"Self Assessment tax returns\">Self Assessment tax return</a> if you fill one in each year. </p>\n\n<p>If you don’t, you call or write to HM Revenue &amp; Customs (<abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr>) to reclaim the extra tax you’ve paid.</p>\n\n<div class=\"contact\">\n<p><strong><abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr> Income Tax enquiries</strong></p>\n\n<p>0845 300 0627<br />\nMonday to Friday 8am to 8pm<br />\nSaturday 8am to 4pm</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"address\"><div class=\"adr org fn\"><p>\n\n<abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr>\n<br />Pay As You Earn\n<br />PO Box 1970\n<br />Liverpool\n<br />L75 1WX\n<br />\n</p></div></div>\n\n<p>If you pay Income Tax at the 50% rate, you can only claim the difference through your <a href=\"/self-assessment-tax-returns\" title=\"Self Assessment tax returns\">Self Assessment tax return.</a></p>\n\n<h2>Limits on tax relief for pension contributions</h2>\n\n<p>The maximum amount of pension contributions that you can get tax relief on in each tax year is the lower of:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>100% of your earnings</li>\n  <li>£50,000</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You pay Income Tax on any pension contributions you make above the limit.</p>\n\n<h2>If you don’t pay Income Tax</h2>\n\n<p>If you don’t pay Income Tax because you’re on a low income, you still automatically get tax relief at 20% on the first £3,600 you pay into a pension each tax year. </p>\n\n<h2>If you pay into someone else&rsquo;s pension</h2>\n\n<p>If you pay into someone else&rsquo;s pension, like your partner or spouse, they can get tax relief on your contributions instead of you. </p>\n\n<p>They&rsquo;ll automatically get the 20% tax relief added to their pension pot if the pension scheme is a &lsquo;relief at source&rsquo; arrangement.</p>\n\n<p>If it&rsquo;s an occupational or workplace pension scheme, check the scheme&rsquo;s rules. If it allows you to make contributions for other people, the person you&rsquo;re paying for may need to claim the tax relief. They should write to or call <abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr>.</p>\n\n<div class=\"address\"><div class=\"adr org fn\"><p>\n\n<abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr>\n<br />Pay As You Earn\n<br />PO Box 1970\n<br />Liverpool\n<br />L75 1WX\n<br />\n</p></div></div>\n\n<div class=\"contact\">\n<p><strong><abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr> Income Tax enquiries</strong></p>\n\n<p>0845 300 0627<br />\nMonday to Friday 8am to 8pm<br />\nSaturday 8am to 4pm</p>\n</div>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/income-tax-reliefs/self-employed-tax-relief","slug":"self-employed-tax-relief","order":3,"title":"Self employed: tax relief","body":"<p>If you’re self-employed (a sole trader or partner in a partnership), you get tax relief on what you spend running your business. </p>\n\n<p>You only pay Income Tax and National Insurance contributions on your profits.</p>\n\n<p>You claim tax relief by filling in your <a href=\"/self-assessment-tax-returns\" title=\"Self Assessment tax returns\">Self Assessment tax return.</a></p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You must claim within 5 years of the end of the tax year that you spent the money.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Costs you can claim</h2>\n\n<p>You can claim tax relief on money that you must spend to run your business. For example:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>wages and salaries you pay to staff</li>\n  <li>the cost of goods for your business (like stock for a retailer or materials for a builder)</li>\n  <li>rent of business premises (like an office or shop)</li>\n  <li>rent, rates, power and water your business premises uses</li>\n  <li>motor and travel expenses if they’re only for business (like visiting customers or delivering goods)</li>\n  <li>bad debts (money your business is owed but isn’t paid)</li>\n  <li>losses your business made in previous tax years</li>\n  <li>accountancy and professional fees</li>\n  <li>advertising</li>\n  <li>business bank, PayPal and credit card charges</li>\n  <li>business insurance</li>\n  <li>interest on business loans</li>\n  <li>a uniform with your business logo on it</li>\n  <li>postage</li>\n  <li>safety clothing that you need for your business</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Costs you can’t claim</h2>\n\n<p>You can’t claim ‘private expenditure’ - money you spend on things that aren’t directly related to your business. For example, you can’t claim:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>day-to-day living expenses, like food or clothing that isn&rsquo;t related to work</li>\n  <li>household expenses</li>\n  <li>the amount you take as wages (sometimes called ‘drawings’)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>If you use something both personally and for business - eg a landline at home - you can only claim for the part of the cost that you’ve used for business.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Equipment, machinery and property</h2>\n\n<p>If you buy equipment or machinery for your business, or things like furniture that you expect to last, you must claim the cost of them in a different way. These are called <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/manuals/pimmanual/pim3005.htm\" title=\"Capital allowances\">&lsquo;capital allowances&rsquo;</a></p>\n\n<h2>More information</h2>\n\n<p>HM Revenue &amp; Customs has more details on what you can and can&rsquo;t claim when you&rsquo;re self employed.</p>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/factsheets/expenses-allowances.pdf\" title=\"Download 'Expenses and allowances for the self-employed: what you need to know' (PDF, 126KB)\" rel=\"external\">Download ‘Expenses and allowances for the self-employed: what you need to know’ (PDF, 126KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/income-tax-reliefs/expenses-if-youre-employed-tax-relief","slug":"expenses-if-youre-employed-tax-relief","order":4,"title":"Expenses if you're employed: tax relief","body":"<p>If you use your own money for travel and things that you must buy for your job, you may be able to claim tax relief for what you&rsquo;ve spent. You must claim within 5 years of the end of the tax year that you spent the money. </p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>If your employer has paid back your expenses, you can’t claim tax relief.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>How to claim</h2>\n\n<p>If you fill in a <a href=\"/self-assessment-tax-returns\" title=\"Self Assessment tax returns\">Self Assessment tax return</a>, you make your claim this way.</p>\n\n<p>If you don&rsquo;t, fill in and send form P87 to HM Revenue &amp; Customs (<abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr>).</p>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/forms/p87.pdf\" title=\"Download 'Form P87 -Tax relief for expenses of employment' (PDF, 70KB)\" rel=\"external\">Download ‘form P87 -Tax relief for expenses of employment’ (PDF, 70KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"address\"><div class=\"adr org fn\"><p>\n\n<abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr>  \n<br />Pay As You Earn  \n<br />PO Box 1970  \n<br />Liverpool  \n<br />L75 1WX  \n<br />\n</p></div></div>\n\n<h2>Travel and fuel costs</h2>\n\n<p>You may be able to get tax relief if you use your <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/incometax/relief-mileage.htm\" title=\"Tax relief on fuel and business mileage\">own vehicle on business or for fuel you buy</a> when you use a company car. </p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You can’t claim for travelling to where you usually work.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>You may be able to get tax relief for the cost of <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/incometax/relief-travel.htm\" title=\"Tax relief on travel and subsistence\">business travel and money you&rsquo;ve had to spend on food or overnight expenses</a> (called &lsquo;subsistence&rsquo;). For example, if you need to visit a client or go to a temporary workplace. </p>\n\n<h2>Working at home</h2>\n\n<p>You may be able to get tax back for some of the bills you have to pay because you’re <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/incometax/relief-household.htm\" title=\"Tax relief for household expenses when you're working at home\">working at home.</a></p>\n\n<h2>Tools and specialist clothing</h2>\n\n<p>If you have to buy <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/incometax/relief-tools.htm\" title=\"Tax relief for tools and specialist clothing\">small tools or buy specialist clothing</a> for your work - like a uniform or protective clothing - you may be able to claim back what you’ve paid.</p>\n\n<h2>Professional fees and subscriptions</h2>\n\n<p>You can ask for tax back on fees or subscriptions you pay to some <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/incometax/relief-subs.htm\" title=\"Tax relief for professional fees and subscriptions\">approved professional organisations</a> - but only if you must have membership to do your job or it&rsquo;s helpful for your work.</p>\n\n<h2>Buying other equipment</h2>\n\n<p>If you buy something like a filing cabinet or a desk for your work - called &lsquo;capital expenditure&rsquo; - you might be able to get <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/incometax/relief-capital.htm\" title=\"Tax relief for capital expenditure\">capital allowances</a> to help with the cost.</p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/income-tax-reliefs/charity-donations-tax-relief","slug":"charity-donations-tax-relief","order":5,"title":"Charity donations: tax relief","body":"<p>Donations to charity get tax relief if you make them through either a:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>Gift Aid scheme</li>\n  <li>Payroll Giving scheme</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Donations through Gift Aid</h2>\n\n<p>Charities and amateur sports clubs can register with HM Revenue &amp; Customs (<abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr>) to be part of the Gift Aid scheme. When they&rsquo;re registered, they can claim back the tax you&rsquo;ve already paid on your donation.</p>\n\n<p>The charity or sports club will give you a form to sign. They must also have an <abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr> charity reference number - ask the charity or sports club if you&rsquo;re not sure.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>If you’ve paid less tax than the charity or sports club gets back, you may be asked to pay the tax to <abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr>.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h3>If you pay Income Tax at 40% or 50%</h3>\n\n<p>You can claim back the difference between the tax you&rsquo;ve paid on the donation and what the charity got back when you fill in your <a href=\"/self-assessment-tax-returns\" title=\"Self Assessment tax returns\">Self Assessment tax return.</a></p>\n\n<h3>If you get age-related Personal Allowances or Married Couple&rsquo;s Allowance</h3>\n\n<p>If you get a higher tax-free Personal Allowance because you&rsquo;re over 65 or you claim Married Couple&rsquo;s Allowance, donations you make through Gift Aid may mean your tax-free allowances increase.</p>\n\n<p>If you fill in a <a href=\"/self-assessment-tax-returns\" title=\"Self Assessment tax returns\">Self Assessment tax return</a>, your allowances will be adjusted automatically if they need to be.</p>\n\n<p>If you don&rsquo;t, call <abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr> to tell them about your charity donations.</p>\n\n<div class=\"contact\">\n<p><strong><abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr> Income Tax enquiries</strong></p>\n\n<p>0845 300 0627<br />\nMonday to Friday 8am to 8pm<br />\nSaturday 8am to 4pm</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Payroll Giving schemes</h2>\n\n<p>If your employer or pension provider offers a Payroll Giving scheme, any donations you give through the scheme will be taken before Income Tax is taken off. </p>\n\n<p>You&rsquo;ll still pay National Insurance contributions on the amount of your donation. But you won&rsquo;t pay any Income Tax on the amount you donate.</p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/income-tax-reliefs/maintenance-payments-tax-relief","slug":"maintenance-payments-tax-relief","order":6,"title":"Maintenance payments: tax relief","body":"<p>Maintenance Payments relief reduces your Income Tax if you make maintenance payments to an ex-spouse or civil partner.  </p>\n\n<p>You can get it if all of the following apply:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>either of you were born before 6 April 1935</li>\n  <li>you’re paying maintenance under a court order after the relationship has ended</li>\n  <li>the payments are for the maintenance of your ex-spouse